{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6615108-4370-46bf-b2ec-e17601adbcfd","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports** are saved to:\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` (newer macOS) or `.crash` files matching your process name. You can also browse them in **Console.app** → Crash Reports.\n\n**Core dumps** (if you want a full dump for `lldb`):\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps (off by default on macOS)\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Run your app — on crash, core goes to:\n/cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\nThen debug with:\n```bash\nlldb /path/to/your/app /cores/core.12345\n```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report alone often gives you the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info without needing a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0f56caaa-e17c-463c-9ff9-c763cd43df57","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what they need to know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user-level crashes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level).\n2. Files have extensions like `.crash` or `.ips` (newer macOS versions use `.ips` JSON format).\n\n\n3. The Console.app utility provides a graphical way to browse and search through these reports.\n4. For core dumps specifically, I can enable them with `ulimit -c unlimited`, which will write them to `/cores/`.","outputTokens":423,"requestId":"204B:2A854:72D6BA:857279:69F011D9"},"id":"311e0769-8953-4e3e-9ef8-20fbdd0807c1","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:48:20.044Z","parentId":"a0cff509-0c49-4db2-bb47-a3351b924439"}
